Replace the current manual layout in dashboard.rs (lines 190-228) which uses:
  let stat_height = if area.height > 30 { 8 } else { 6 };
  let stat_area = Rect::new(area.x, area.y, area.width, stat_height);
  let col_width = area.width / 3;
  let col1 = Rect::new(area.x, area.y, col_width, area.height);
With Flex-based responsive layout:
  Xs/Sm: Single column - stat summary (2 lines) + event log (fill)
  Md: Top row (stat tiles, 30%) + event log (fill) + footer (fixed 3)
  Lg: 2-column - left (stat tiles + event log) + right sidebar (agents/alerts, 30%)
  Xl: 3-column - left sidebar (agents, 20%) + center (stat tiles + events, fill) + right (alerts/sparklines, 25%)
The stat tiles area itself uses Flex::horizontal() to split into columns.
Must use Flex::vertical().constraints([...]).split(area) not manual Rect::new().

description:
In crates/mcp-agent-mail-core/src/metrics.rs:

1. In Log2Histogram::record() (line ~170):
   Change the LAST atomic operation (count.fetch_add) from Ordering::Relaxed to Ordering::Release.
   This ensures that all prior writes (sum, min, max, buckets) are visible to any thread that reads count with Acquire ordering.

   Current:  self.count.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);
   Target:   self.count.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Release);

2. In Log2Histogram::snapshot() (line ~192):
   Change the FIRST atomic load (count.load) from Ordering::Relaxed to Ordering::Acquire.
   This ensures that all writes that happened-before the count increment are visible.

   Current:  let count = self.count.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
   Target:   let count = self.count.load(Ordering::Acquire);

All other loads in snapshot() can remain Relaxed because the Acquire on count establishes the happens-before edge.

PERFORMANCE NOTE: This adds exactly 1 memory barrier per snapshot() call (called ~1/second by the TUI poller) and 1 per record() call. On x86_64, Release/Acquire are free (x86 has strong memory ordering). On ARM, they cost a single DMB instruction. The hot path (record) was already doing 5 atomic ops; one extra fence is negligible.

Even with the Acquire/Release fence, there is a tiny window where a concurrent record() could increment count AFTER our Acquire load but BEFORE we read the corresponding bucket. This means bucket_sum could be less than count.

Add post-read clamping at the end of Log2Histogram::snapshot():

    // Ensure mathematical invariants hold despite concurrent updates.
    let min = self.min.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
    let max = self.max.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
    let (min, max) = if count > 0 && min > max { (max, min) } else { (min, max) };
    let min = if count == 0 { 0 } else { min };

This ensures:
- min <= max (swap if violated)
- min is 0 when count is 0 (not u64::MAX from the initial sentinel)
- The p50/p95/p99 estimates use the clamped count for quantile thresholds

The existing code already handles count==0 correctly (returns all zeros). This adds the min/max swap for the count>0 case.

Location: crates/mcp-agent-mail-core/src/metrics.rs (snapshot method, around line 208-220)

Create a new helper function in crates/mcp-agent-mail-tools/src/messaging.rs:

    /// Sanitize a thread_id that may come from legacy data or derived values.
    /// Unlike is_valid_thread_id() which rejects invalid input, this function
    /// cleans the input to produce a valid thread_id, logging a warning if
    /// any sanitization was needed.
    fn sanitize_thread_id(tid: &str) -> String {
        if is_valid_thread_id(tid) {
            return tid.to_string();
        }
        tracing::warn!(
            original = tid,
            "sanitizing invalid thread_id from legacy/derived data"
        );
        // Strip invalid characters, ensure starts with alphanumeric, truncate to 128
        let sanitized: String = tid.chars()
            .filter(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || *c == '.' || *c == '_' || *c == '-')
            .take(128)
            .collect();
        // Ensure starts with alphanumeric
        if sanitized.is_empty() || !sanitized.as_bytes()[0].is_ascii_alphanumeric() {
            // Fallback: use a hash of the original
            format!("legacy-{:x}", hash(tid))
        } else {
            sanitized
        }
    }

This is a SANITIZER not a VALIDATOR — it always produces valid output, never rejects. This is critical because reply_message should never fail due to inherited thread_id issues.

Location: crates/mcp-agent-mail-tools/src/messaging.rs (near is_valid_thread_id, ~line 102)

In crates/mcp-agent-mail-db/src/queries.rs, modify get_inbox_stats (line ~1894) to check the ReadCache before querying the database:

1. At the top of the function, check the cache:
       if let Some(cached) = read_cache().get_inbox_stats(agent_id) {
           return Outcome::Ok(Some(cached));
       }

2. After a successful DB query that returns a row, populate the cache:
       read_cache().put_inbox_stats(&stats);

3. If the DB returns no row, do NOT cache the absence (cache is for positive hits only).

IMPORTANT: The read_cache() function must already be available in queries.rs (it is — it is used for project and agent caches). Follow the same pattern as get_project_by_slug or get_agent.

This reduces DB round-trips for the most frequently polled endpoint (fetch_inbox calls get_inbox_stats on every invocation).

Location: crates/mcp-agent-mail-db/src/queries.rs (get_inbox_stats, ~line 1894)

In crates/mcp-agent-mail-db/src/queries.rs, modify create_message_with_recipients:

After successfully inserting recipients, invalidate inbox stats for EACH recipient:

    for (recipient_id, _kind) in recipients {
        read_cache().invalidate_inbox_stats(*recipient_id);
    }

This ensures that when a new message is sent, each recipient's cached inbox stats (total_count, unread_count) are invalidated so the next fetch_inbox call sees the new message.

NOTE: Do NOT invalidate the sender's stats — the sender's inbox is unaffected by sending.

Location: crates/mcp-agent-mail-db/src/queries.rs (create_message_with_recipients)
